  Production (Let's Encrypt)

  Requires a public domain name pointing to your server.

  Certbot (most common):
  # Install
  apt install certbot

  # Standalone mode (temporarily binds port 80)
  sudo certbot certonly --standalone -d yourdomain.com

  # Certs are at:
  # /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem
  # /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem

  Run the server:
  sudo ./dist/server --tls \
    /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem \
    /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem

  Let's Encrypt certs expire every 90 days. Auto-renew:
  sudo certbot renew --pre-hook "pkill server" --post-hook "sudo ./dist/server ..."
  # or just renew the cert and send SIGHUP/restart the server

  ---
  Key point

  Always use fullchain.pem (not just cert.pem) for Let's Encrypt — it includes the intermediate CA that browsers need to verify the
  chain.


---
● For LAN without a domain, you have two practical options:

  Option 1: Self-signed with IP SAN (simplest)

  Browsers reject self-signed certs for bare IPs unless you add a Subject Alternative Name:

  openssl req -x509 -newkey rsa:2048 \
    -keyout key.pem -out cert.pem \
    -days 3650 -nodes \
    -subj '/CN=192.168.1.100' \
    -addext 'subjectAltName=IP:192.168.1.100'

  Replace 192.168.1.100 with your server's LAN IP.

  Result: browser shows a "Not Secure" warning once — user clicks "Advanced → Proceed". After that it works. Fine for personal/internal
  tools.

  ---
  Option 2: Local CA with mkcert (best for LAN teams)

  https://github.com/FiloSottile/mkcert creates a local certificate authority and installs it into the system/browser trust stores so no
  warnings appear.

  # Install (Arch/Debian/etc)
  sudo pacman -S mkcert    # or: apt install mkcert

  # On the server machine: create local CA
  mkcert -install

  # Generate cert for LAN IP (or hostname)
  mkcert 192.168.1.100 localhost 127.0.0.1
  # produces: 192.168.1.100+2.pem  192.168.1.100+2-key.pem

  Run the server:
  sudo ./dist/server --tls 192.168.1.100+2.pem 192.168.1.100+2-key.pem

  For other users on the LAN: they need to install your CA once:
  # Copy mkcert's rootCA.pem to their machine, then:
  mkcert -CAROOT   # shows where it lives on the server
  # On client: import rootCA.pem into browser/system trust store

